e -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSociocultural anthropologists have taken increasing interest in the global communities established by Roman Catholic and Protestant churches, but the many streams of Eastern Christianity have so far been neglected. Eastern Christians in Anthropological Perspective fills this gap in the literature. The essays in this pioneering collection examine the primary distinguishing features of the Eastern traditions—iconography, hymnology, ritual, and pilgrimage—through meticulous ethnographic analysis. Particular attention is paid to the revitalization of Orthodox and Greek Catholic churches that were repressed under Marxist-Leninist regimes.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAnthropology. 4aGeneral. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aAgadjanian, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowmann, Glenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Melissa L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCouroucli, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngelhardt, Jeffers, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForbess, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoltz, Hermann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoltz, Hermann, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHanganu, Gabriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHann, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHann, Chris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabul